Please note, everywhere it says “branchname” replace that with the name of your chosen branch.

## Branching

A branch is a unique copy of a project on GitHub. It is separate from other branches and changes made on a branch are not necessarily reflected in the project itself on GitHub, just the branch you are working on.

In capstone, the structure of a project should look as following

##### Prod/Main/Production:

*   *   This is the version of the project currently in use by customers - you will never pull from or push to this

##### Stable:

*   *   This is a stable version of the project that is more up to date than the current Prod branch. You also will not pull from or push to this.

##### Integration:

*   *   This is the branch that is actively being used. Students will push to and pull from this branch, and when starting a new issue, branch off of this branch. This is the ‘living’ project.

##### Feature Branch / User Stories:

*   *   These are the individual branches that developers are working from. **\*DO NOT TOUCH THESE BRANCHES WITHOUT PERMISSION FROM THE BRANCH DEVELOPER\***

## Etiquette

*   Do not use other people's development branches unless permission is given (i.e. quality checks)
*   When done with your feature, pull from the integration branch. Fix merge issues (if present), (possibly) ask QA to check your code, when confirmed everything works, create a merge request to the integration branch

## Useful Commands:

#### git branch

*   *   Shows the branches loaded to your machine. The branch with an asterisk (\*) next to it is the branch you are currently working within.

#### git checkout branchname

*   *   Moves you to the branch entered.

#### git status

*   *   Shows the current status of your branch and the files within it.

#### git checkout -b branchname

*   *   Creates a new branch and switches to it.

## Uploading Your Changes To Github

*   The following 2 commands need to be run everytime you want to push to github
    *   git add .
    *   git commit -m “Information about this push” - Saves changes to your local repository
*   git push -u origin branchname
    *   This command only needs to be run once. If youre on branch abc and run this once you will not need to run it again but if you switch to branch def then you will need to run it again, and every time you move to another branch (even if you’ve used it before)
*   git push
    *   After you have run the previous command, this is what you will use to push updates to github - **ENSURE YOU ARE PUSHING TO YOUR OWN BRANCH, YOU ARE WORKING FROM - CHECK WHAT BRANCH YOU ARE ON WITH git branch**

## Pulling Changes From Github

### git pull origin branchname

*   *   Downloads updates from github, and merges them with your local branch
    *   when you want to pull from integration, do git pull origin integration
        *   This pulls updates from integration into your current branch

## Seeing Other Users' Branches

*   git fetch origin
*   git branch -r
    *   This command lists all branches available on github, -r represents remote so this command finds all remote branches
*   git checkout -b branchname origin/branchname
